Superior Watchlist Management

Superior Watchlist Management

As the regulatory landscape continues to evolve and remediation time along with the cost of compliance increases, compliance teams face complex challenges ahead managing regulatory and commercial watchlists. Businesses need an efficient solution to ingest and harmonise diverse data sources whilst meeting regulatory obligations.

Benefits for Compliance Teams

Benefits for Compliance

Teams

Benefits for Compliance

Teams

  • Efficiency and Cost Reduction 

    Increased Efficiency

    Automates manual tasks, freeing your team to focus on high-priority compliance decisions.

    Operational Optimisation

    Establish a rapid, robust, and end-to-end watchlist data management process, ensuring watchlist management excellence at the quickest pace possible. 

    Cost Savings

    Reduces reliance on manual labour for time-consuming watchlist management tasks, freeing teams to focus on higher-value, critical compliance activities while significantly lowering the costs associated with manual data handling and reconciliation. 

  • Data Accuracy and Compliance Assurance 

    Improved Data Accuracy

    Reduces errors through automated reconciliation and data cleansing.

    Enhanced Screening Confidence

    Keeps your process aligned with constantly evolving global regulations.

    Future-Proof Operations

    Ensures agility in responding to new regulations and growing volumes of data.

  • Workflow and Audit Transparency

    Streamlined Workflows

    Seamlessly connects all aspects of watchlist management with downstream screening engines (e.g., Customer Screening, Transaction Screening), so that the latest and most relevant data is always in-scope.

    Tailored Processes

    Configurable templates and workflows ensure precision in data delivery. 

    Audit-Ready Transparency

    Provides comprehensive, easily accessible audit history for all system changes (such as record updates, watchlist updates, reconciliation updates, and template changes).
